# THE SHARED TEST-FILE REVISION THIS REPOSITORY ADOPTED, BY CONTENT.
#
# The five files below are not this repository's work. They are ~1700
# lines COPIED from the compiler repository's fleet/templates/. Nothing
# noticed when a copy diverged, which has already happened twice in this
# fleet: a capability tuple hand-copied at 21 sites that had already
# drifted, and check_tag_version.sh becoming a second copy whose two
# versions immediately printed different messages.
#
# TWO KINDS OF ENTRY, and the difference matters when you edit one.
#
#   tests/test_release_wiring.sh and tests/test_wiring_mutations.sh have
#   to say repo-specific things, so each carries a CONFIG block. The
#   number below covers everything OUTSIDE that block. Edit the block;
#   never edit below it.
#
#   tests/test_shared_regions.sh, tests/test_guard_pins.sh and
#   .github/workflows/checks.yml carry no repo-specific configuration at
#   all, so the number below covers the WHOLE file. There is nothing in
#   any of them for you to edit. If you need to, say so upstream rather
#   than forking it here: a config block is the one part of a shared
#   file that nothing digests, and adding one to carry a single flag
#   would open exactly the hole the grammar in test_shared_regions.sh
#   exists to close. If this repository needs more CI, add a SEPARATE
#   workflow rather than editing checks.yml; that is what every adopter
#   with extra checks has done.
#
# So this file records the SHA-256 of each, and
# tests/test_shared_regions.sh checks it two ways:
#
#   1. OFFLINE, by digesting the local files and comparing. This never
#      skips, and it catches the ordinary case, an edit below the line.
#   2. ONLINE, by fetching the canonical file at the revision named
#      below and digesting THAT with the same code. Layer 1 compares a
#      file in this repository against a number in this repository, so
#      anyone who edits a body can regenerate the number and go green.
#      Layer 2 is what makes the number honest. It reports SKIP without
#      `gh`, matching tests/test_release_wiring.sh.
#
# THE `revision` LINE BELOW IS NOT THE GUARD PIN. .github/guard-pins.sha256
# has its own, and the two are deliberately independent: a single shared
# revision would make every guard bump force a wiring re-audit and every
# wiring bump force a guard re-audit, and that friction is the likeliest
# reason for either audit to be skipped altogether.
#
# TO ADOPT, AND TO RE-PIN: do not edit this file by hand. Run, from a
# checkout of the compiler repository,
#
#   bash fleet/adopt.sh <this repository> <compiler revision>
#
# which installs all five files and writes every digest below FROM THAT
# REVISION. The hand procedure it replaces had one step that could go
# wrong silently: copying these numbers from another adopter. If that
# adopter is one revision stale, layer 1 goes green, because the files
# came from the same stale place, and layer 2 goes red, and the obvious
# response is to bump the revision until it passes. That is the fork the
# paragraph below warns about, reached by trying to fix a red test.
#
# ADD `* text eol=lf` TO .gitattributes IF IT IS NOT THERE ALREADY. The
# check matches marker lines by whole-line equality and reads this file
# field by field. A CRLF checkout is handled explicitly on both sides,
# so it will not produce a wrong answer, but a repository whose files
# flip line endings per platform will produce diffs and digests that
# depend on who committed last, and the release tarball's digest is
# covered by a signature.
#
# TO RE-ADOPT AFTER AN UPSTREAM CHANGE: read the diff between the two
# revisions, re-copy all five files, keep your CONFIG blocks in the two
# that have them, then update the revision and the digests together.
# Updating the digests without re-copying is how a local edit becomes a
# permanent fork with a green test over it.

# The revision below must be a FULL 40-character commit SHA of the
# compiler repository, and `bash fleet/adopt.sh` is what writes it. The
# value shipped in the template is deliberately not 40 hex characters,
# so that a copy nobody edited reddens OFFLINE on the first run rather
# than waiting for a network fetch to fail.
#
# This comment is worded to stay true after adoption. It used to
# describe the placeholder in the present tense, which meant every
# adopted copy carried a sentence calling a real SHA a placeholder.
